  summary: 'A 45-year-old hypertensive accountant presented with an 8-month history of recurrent unilateral throbbing headaches preceded by visual aura and associated with nausea, occasional vomiting, photophobia and phonophobia, consistent with migraine with aura.',
  content: `
NEUROLOGY CLINIC

Patient Seen

A 45-year-old married accountant from Abeokuta, Ogun State, Christian, Yoruba.

PC:
Recurrent severe headache × 8 months.

HPC:
The patient was apparently well until about eight months prior to presentation when he developed recurrent episodes of severe headache occurring approximately two to three times monthly. The headaches have become more frequent over the preceding three months.

The headache is predominantly unilateral, usually affecting the right frontotemporal region but occasionally involving the left side. It is throbbing and pulsatile in nature with a severity of 8–9/10 and lasts between 6 and 24 hours if untreated, significantly interfering with daily activities.

Each episode is usually preceded by a visual aura lasting approximately 20 minutes, characterized by flashing lights and shimmering zigzag lines in the right visual field. During the headache, he experiences nausea, occasional vomiting, photophobia and phonophobia and prefers to lie in a dark, quiet room until symptoms improve.

Common triggers include emotional stress, sleep deprivation, prolonged computer work and skipping meals. The headache is aggravated by ordinary physical activity such as climbing stairs or bending.

Partial relief is obtained with sleep and over-the-counter Paracetamol or Ibuprofen.

No history of thunderclap headache, progressive worsening in severity, headache precipitated by coughing, straining or postural change, fever, neck stiffness, confusion, loss of consciousness, seizures, limb weakness, numbness, speech difficulty, facial deviation, persistent visual loss, diplopia or recent head injury.

No history of malignancy, immunosuppression, chronic anticoagulant use or poorly controlled hypertension.

This is his first hospital presentation for these symptoms.

ROS:

Neurological:
Recurrent unilateral headache.
Visual aura.
Photophobia.
Phonophobia.
Occasional nausea and vomiting.
No weakness.
No sensory deficit.
No gait disturbance.

Ophthalmic:
Transient flashing lights preceding headaches.
No persistent visual impairment.
No eye pain.

ENT:
No nasal congestion.
No sinus tenderness.
No ear discharge.

Cardiovascular:
No chest pain.
No palpitations.

Constitutional:
No fever.
No weight loss.
Appetite preserved.

PMH:
Known hypertensive diagnosed two years ago, well controlled.
No diabetes mellitus.
No previous stroke.
No epilepsy.
No chronic kidney disease.
No previous neurosurgical procedures.

Drug History:
Tab Amlodipine 5 mg daily.
Occasional Paracetamol and Ibuprofen for headaches.
No known drug allergies.

Family History:
Mother has recurrent migraine headaches.
No family history of stroke or brain tumours.

Social History:
Works as an accountant with prolonged computer use.
Frequently skips meals because of work.
Sleeps approximately 5–6 hours nightly.
Consumes two cups of coffee daily.
Occasional alcohol intake.
Does not smoke.
No recreational drug use.

O/E:
Middle-aged man, conscious, alert and oriented.
Comfortable at the time of examination.
Not pale, anicteric, afebrile and well hydrated.
No peripheral oedema.

Vitals:
BP: 126/78 mmHg
PR: 74 bpm, regular
RR: 16 cpm
Temperature: 36.7°C
SpO₂: 99% on room air
Weight: 82 kg
Height: 1.76 m
BMI: 26.5 kg/m² (Overweight)

Neurological Examination:
GCS 15/15.
Cranial nerves II–XII intact.
Visual acuity normal.
Visual fields full to confrontation.
Fundoscopy revealed healthy optic discs without papilloedema.
Normal muscle bulk and tone.
Power 5/5 in all limbs.
Deep tendon reflexes 2+ bilaterally.
Plantar responses flexor.
Sensation intact.
Finger-nose and heel-shin tests normal.
Normal gait.
No meningeal signs.

CVS:
Pulse regular.
S1 and S2 heard only.
No murmurs.

Respiratory:
Chest clinically clear.
Vesicular breath sounds.

Abdomen:
Soft.
Non-tender.
No organomegaly.

ASS:
Migraine with aura.

DDX:
Migraine without aura.
Episodic tension-type headache.
Cluster headache.
Chronic daily headache secondary to medication-overuse.
Intracranial space-occupying lesion (less likely).
Temporal arteritis (unlikely).
Cervicogenic headache.

INVESTIGATIONS:
FBC.
Electrolytes, Urea and Creatinine.
Fasting Blood Sugar.
Liver Function Tests.

If clinically indicated:
ESR/CRP if temporal arteritis is suspected.
CT Brain or MRI Brain only if red flag symptoms, abnormal neurological examination, atypical headache features or sudden change in headache pattern develop.
Visual assessment if persistent visual symptoms occur.

PLAN:

Acute Attack:
Rest in a quiet, dark room.
Maintain adequate hydration.
Avoid driving until symptoms resolve.

Medications:

Option 1:
Tab Naproxen 500 mg immediately at onset, then 500 mg every 12 hours if required (maximum 1 g/day).
Tab Omeprazole 20 mg daily while on NSAIDs.

OR

Tab Ibuprofen 400–600 mg immediately at onset (maximum 2.4 g/day).

OR

Tab Paracetamol 1 g immediately at onset (maximum 4 g/day).

Preferred for Moderate to Severe Migraine:
Tab Sumatriptan 50 mg immediately at onset.
Repeat once after 2 hours if required (maximum 200 mg/day).

OR

Tab Rizatriptan 10 mg at onset.
Repeat after 2 hours if necessary (maximum 30 mg/day).

Avoid triptans in patients with ischaemic heart disease, uncontrolled hypertension or previous stroke.

For Nausea:
Tab Metoclopramide 10 mg orally three times daily as required.
OR
IV/IM Metoclopramide 10 mg stat if unable to tolerate oral medication.

Preventive Therapy (if ≥4 headache days/month or significant disability):
Tab Propranolol 40 mg twice daily, titrating to 80–160 mg/day.

OR

Tab Amitriptyline 10 mg nocte, increasing gradually to 25–50 mg nocte.

OR

Tab Topiramate 25 mg nocte for one week, increasing gradually to 50 mg twice daily as tolerated.

OR

Tab Sodium Valproate 250 mg twice daily, increasing gradually to 500 mg twice daily if required.

Lifestyle Modification:
Maintain regular sleep.
Avoid skipping meals.
Maintain adequate hydration.
Limit caffeine intake.
Exercise regularly.
Reduce stress.
Identify and avoid migraine triggers.
Keep a headache diary.
Avoid excessive analgesic use to prevent medication-overuse headache.

Patient Education:
Explained that migraine is a chronic neurological disorder with effective treatment options.
Advised early use of medications at headache onset.
Instructed to seek urgent medical attention if headache becomes sudden and severe or is associated with fever, seizures, confusion, persistent neurological deficits, visual loss or altered consciousness.

Follow-up:
Review in 4 weeks with headache diary to assess symptom frequency, treatment response and need for preventive therapy.
Earlier review if headaches become more frequent, refractory to treatment or if red flag symptoms develop.
`,
