  content: `
GENERAL OUTPATIENT CLINIC

Patient Seen

A 25-year-old Yoruba female fashion designer residing in Ibadan, Oyo State.

PC:
Epigastric pain × 5 months
Worsening of pain × 3 days

HPC:
Patient was apparently well until about 5 months prior to presentation when she developed recurrent epigastric pain. The pain is described as burning and gnawing in character, moderately severe, and occasionally radiates to the back. It is typically worse at night and about 2–3 hours after meals but is temporarily relieved by food intake and over-the-counter antacids.

She had a similar episode 3 months ago and was diagnosed with peptic ulcer disease at a local pharmacy. She completed a one-week course of triple therapy (specific medications unknown), with temporary resolution of symptoms. However, the symptoms recurred about 4 weeks ago and have progressively worsened over the last 3 days.

There is associated heartburn, acid regurgitation, and occasional nausea.

No history of vomiting, hematemesis, melena, significant weight loss, early satiety, or dysphagia.

Past Medical History:
Diagnosed with peptic ulcer disease 3 months ago.
No history of hypertension, diabetes mellitus, or asthma.
Genotype AA.
No previous surgeries or blood transfusions.

Drug History:
Frequent use of OTC Ibuprofen 400 mg as required for primary dysmenorrhea over the past 2 years.
Currently taking OTC Omeprazole 20 mg daily and Gestid suspension for the past 2 weeks with minimal improvement.
No known drug allergies.

Family/Social History:
Single and lives with her family in a rented apartment.
Does not smoke cigarettes or consume alcohol.
Reports significant occupational stress.

ROS:
GIT: As above. No jaundice. Normal bowel habits.
CVS: No chest pain or palpitations.
RS: No cough or dyspnea.
CNS: No headache or dizziness.
GUT: Normal menstrual cycle with mild dysmenorrhea.

O/E:
Young woman, conscious and alert, in mild painful distress.
Not pale, anicteric, acyanosed, and well hydrated.
No peripheral lymphadenopathy or pedal edema.

Temp: 36.5°C
PR: 76 bpm, regular, normal volume
RR: 16 cpm
BP: 110/70 mmHg
SpO₂: 99% on room air

ABD:
Flat, moves with respiration.
Mild to moderate epigastric tenderness.
No guarding or rigidity.
No palpable organomegaly.
Bowel sounds present and normal.

CVS:
S1 and S2 heard only. No murmurs.

RS:
Chest clinically clear.
Vesicular breath sounds bilaterally.

CNS:
Conscious and alert.
No focal neurological deficits.

ASS:
Recurrent peptic ulcer disease, likely duodenal ulcer secondary to chronic NSAID use and/or Helicobacter pylori treatment failure.

Differentials:
Gastroesophageal reflux disease.
Chronic cholecystitis/Biliary colic.
Functional dyspepsia.

PLAN:

Investigations:
Full blood count.
H. pylori stool antigen test.
Abdominal ultrasound scan.
Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy if symptoms persist after treatment or if alarm features develop.

Lifestyle Modifications:
Strict avoidance of NSAIDs.
Use Paracetamol 1 g as required for dysmenorrhea.
Dietary counselling including avoidance of spicy, fatty, and acidic foods.
Avoid skipping meals.
Stress reduction measures.

Medications:
Tab Omeprazole 20 mg bd (or Esomeprazole 40 mg daily) for 4 weeks.
Liquid Mucaine or Gestid suspension 10 mL tds between meals and at bedtime as required.

If H. pylori stool antigen is positive:
Tab Omeprazole 20 mg bd.
Tab Amoxicillin 1 g bd.
Tab Clarithromycin 500 mg bd for 10–14 days.

Follow-up:
Review in 2 weeks to assess symptom control and treatment compliance.

Patient was counselled to present immediately if she develops hematemesis, melena, sudden severe abdominal pain, or persistent vomiting.
`,
